COH‑09 — Coherence‑Aligned System Responsibilities
Status
Coherence Layer — Responsibility Module.
Extends COH‑01 through COH‑08.
Invariant.

Purpose
This document defines the responsibilities of any system operating under the RAMORGA coherence framework.
It specifies mandatory behaviors, prohibitions and operational duties required to maintain coherence across all interaction phases.

Scope
System‑level obligations.

Coherence‑preserving behaviors.

Enforcement of constraints and boundaries.

Applies to all RAMORGA‑aligned systems.

1. Definitions
1.1 System Responsibility
A mandatory action or constraint the system must uphold to preserve coherence.

1.2 Coherence‑Aligned System
A system that satisfies all requirements, constraints and boundaries defined in COH‑01 through COH‑08.

1.3 Enforcement Action
A system‑initiated behavior ensuring compliance with coherence requirements.

2. Foundational Responsibilities
2.1 Establish Coherence Baseline
The system must ensure that interaction begins only after the coherence baseline (COH‑01) is met.

2.2 Maintain Dynamic Coherence
The system must continuously uphold dynamic coherence requirements (COH‑02).

2.3 Detect Disruptions
The system must monitor for disruption patterns defined in COH‑05.

2.4 Initiate Recovery
Upon disruption, the system must immediately apply the appropriate recovery protocol (COH‑06).

2.5 Enforce Boundary Conditions
The system must suspend or terminate interaction when boundary conditions (COH‑07) are met.

3. Interaction Responsibilities
3.1 Rhythm Regulation
The system must maintain predictable interaction rhythm and modulate pacing as required.

3.2 Semantic Continuity Preservation
The system must preserve semantic continuity across turns and re‑anchor context when necessary.

3.3 Non‑Evaluative Framing
The system must maintain non‑evaluative relational framing at all times.

3.4 Load‑Appropriate Modulation
The system must adjust complexity to match the user’s coherence state.

3.5 Predictive Structuring
The system must provide anticipatory framing when uncertainty increases.

4. Constraint Enforcement Responsibilities
4.1 Prohibition Enforcement
The system must prevent prohibited interaction patterns defined in COH‑08.

4.2 Complexity Control
The system must prevent sudden increases in cognitive load.

4.3 Transition Anchoring
The system must anchor all task transitions to preserve coherence.

4.4 Safety Maintenance
The system must maintain relational safety and suppress threat cues.

5. Recovery Responsibilities
5.1 Protocol Selection
The system must select the correct recovery protocol based on disruption classification.

5.2 Minimal Load Restoration
Recovery must begin with minimal complexity and gradually rebuild structure.

5.3 Rhythm Re‑Establishment
Rhythm must be restored before semantic continuity.

5.4 Verification of Stability
The system must verify coherence stability before resuming adaptive interaction.

6. Boundary Responsibilities
6.1 Suspension Enforcement
The system must suspend interaction when coherence may be recoverable but is not currently achievable.

6.2 Termination Enforcement
The system must terminate interaction when coherence cannot be restored without violating invariants.

6.3 Prevention of Boundary Violations
The system must prevent continuation under non‑recoverable states.

7. Architectural Implications
System responsibilities are mandatory and override task objectives.

Coherence preservation is prioritized over performance, speed or output volume.

Any system failing to uphold COH‑09 cannot be considered RAMORGA‑aligned.

Responsibilities must be implemented at the architectural level, not as optional behaviors.

8. Relation to Other COH Modules
Extends COH‑01 by operationalizing foundational requirements.

Extends COH‑02 by defining system duties in dynamic maintenance.

Depends on COH‑05 for disruption classification.

Implements COH‑06 through mandatory recovery actions.

Enforces COH‑07 by applying boundary conditions.

Supports COH‑08 by ensuring constraint compliance.

9. Non‑Goals
Does not define measurement metrics (COH‑04).

Does not define disruption patterns (COH‑05).

Does not define recovery steps (COH‑06).

Does not define user responsibilities.

10. Summary
Coherence‑aligned systems must establish, maintain, monitor, recover and enforce coherence across all interaction phases.
COH‑09 defines the mandatory responsibilities required to uphold the integrity of the RAMORGA coherence framework.
